<h3> (3) Edge-localized states in 1D quantum lattices </h3>



<p>
The study of a few quantum particles in finite lattices
reveals phenomena distinct from issues in bulk condensed
matter physics.  In one-dimensional quantum lattice models
with open boundaries, we study localization at the lattice
edge.  We show that edge-localized eigenstates can be found
in both bosonic and fermionic systems, specifically, in the
Bose-Hubbard model with on-site interactions and in the
spinless fermion model with nearest-neighbor interactions.
In contrast to localization induced by impurities/disorder,
this is a collective rather than a single-particle effect,
requiring at least three fermions or three bosons.


<p>
Reference:  
<BR>
R. Pinto, M. Haque, S. Flach, arXiv:0902.3249.  



